The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 The City Diary

 Calcutta High Court on Wednesday directed Augustine Public School, in Howrah, to issue transfer certificates to students who had passed ICSE 2006. The order said the authorities must issue the certificates within five days of their submission of the marksheets. The ICSE council, following a difference of opinion with the school, had asked 25 students to appear for the exams from Don Bosco School, Liluah. But after the publication of the results, the school refused to issue transfer certificates to the students.

 A four-member gang barged into a house on Indra Roy Road, in Bhowanipore, and decamped with cash and jewellery worth Rs 60,000 early on Wednesday. Police said the criminals entered the house of Shyamal Chowdhury after breaking open the window grilles. No one has been arrested.

 Arshad Rahaman, a former Customs employee, was arrested in Jadavpur on Tuesday night on charges of extortion. Acting on a tip-off, police laid a trap at Jubilee Market and caught Rahaman while he was demanding money from the owner of a jewellery shop.

 Power supply will be disrupted in several areas on Thursday, as the CESC will carry out repairs at the Talpukur distribution station. Supply in Beleghata, Narkeldanga, Talpukur, Munshibazar, Garpar, Raja RL Mitra Road, Chaulputty and Barwaritala may be affected from 1 am to 3 pm. Maintenance work at the Behala (north) distribution station will affect supply in the Chanditala, SN Roy Road-Diamond Harbour Road crossing, Buroshibtala Main Road, James Long Sarani and Raibahadur Road areas between 10.30 am and 4.30 pm on July 26.

 The Asian Development Bank has sanctioned Rs 450 crore to the Calcutta Environment Improvement Project for its second phase of work in Tiljala, Kasba, Tangra and other areas. The project involves augmentation of the sewerage and water supply systems, urban development minister Asok Bhattacharya said on Wednesday. 

 A bill banning use of plastic bags will soon be tabled in the Assembly, the municipal affairs department said on Wednesday. Sources said the bill would have a provision of imposing a fine of Rs 500 on anyone found throwing plastic bags on roads or in drains.

 Rajib Das, a 32-year-old CPM activist, was shot at by a gang in Dakshineswar on Tuesday night. Police said Das was returning home on a motorcycle when he was attacked. He was admitted to hospital in a critical condition. Praveen Kumar, superintendent of police, North 24-Parganas, said three persons have been arrested. 

 Gopinath Naskar, in his middle age, was arrested in Mahestala, on the southern fringes of the city, on Tuesday on charges of assaulting a pregnant woman. Police are also looking for his son Aloke on the same charge. On Tuesday, Aloke had allegedly made obscene gestures at the woman. As she protested, Aloke and Gopinath beat her up. She has been admitted to Vidyasagar Hospital, in Behala.

